{
  "text": "We recently developed a new assessment for the fall risk of older individuals, the multi-target stepping (MTS) test, to measure stepping accuracy in a simplified manner [CITATION_1] . In the MTS test, participants were asked to walk while stepping on multiple footfall targets and avoiding non-targets. In one of the studies to validate the MTS test [CITATION_2] , we compared gaze behaviors while performing the MTS test among the three groups: the older individuals who are at high risk (HR) of falling (HR older), those who are at low risk (LR) www.frontiersin.org of falling (LR older), and young individuals. The results showed that whereas the younger participants fixated approximately three targets ahead, the older participants directed their fixation closer toward the imminent footfall target. Such a tendency was significantly higher for the HR older participants than the LR older participants (Figure 3) . Furthermore, the closer toward the imminent footfall target their fixations were, the more frequent were the errors of failure in stepping on the target and of avoiding non-targets.",
